{
  "query": "How do you ask a B2B SaaS customer for a testimonial or quote? Email/Slack/in-person ask structure: relationship-grounded opening, specific business outcome, what you'll use it for, time commitment, easy-yes pre-drafted quote option, gratitude. What are the failure modes — generic asks, too-long emails, no draft for them to react to, asking too soon in the relationship?",
  "text": "## The ask that actually works\n\nMost testimonial requests fail before the customer even finishes reading them. The failure isn't the relationship or the product. It's the ask itself: generic, effortful, and timed wrong.\n\nHere's the structure that works, whether you're sending an email, a Slack message, or setting up a 10-minute call.\n\n---\n\n## The anatomy of a good ask\n\n**Lead with their specific outcome, not your need.** \"You mentioned on our last call that you cut reporting time by 40%\" lands differently than \"We're building out our customer story library.\" One is about them. The other is about you.\n\n**Be explicit about what you'll use it for.** \"A short quote for our sales deck and website\" sets expectations. Customers get nervous when they don't know where their words will end up.\n\n**Name the time commitment.** \"Five minutes, max\" is a green light. Vague requests feel like a trap.\n\n**Pre-draft the quote for them.** This is the single highest-leverage move in the whole process. Something like: \"Here's a starting point you can edit however you'd like: *'[Company] helped us reduce X by Y, which meant Z for our team.'*\" Most customers will accept it with minor tweaks. You've done the hard work. They just approve it.\n\n**Close with a simple yes/no.** \"Does that work?\" or \"Happy to adjust the draft if it doesn't quite fit.\" Easy exit, low pressure.\n\n---\n\n## The failure modes worth knowing\n\n**Generic asks.** \"Would you be willing to share a testimonial?\" The customer has no idea what to say, so they say nothing or punt it forever.\n\n**Too long.** If the email takes more than 45 seconds to read, you've already lost them. Cut everything that doesn't serve the ask.\n\n**No draft.** Asking someone to write from scratch is asking for a favor that feels like work. A pre-drafted quote flips the cognitive load entirely.\n\n**Asking too soon.** The right moment is right after a specific win, not at a quarterly check-in or renewal call. When they've just told you something worked, that's the window. It closes fast.\n\n**Asking the wrong person.** The champion loves you. But the quote needs to come from someone with a title that resonates with your buyer. Think about who your prospect will actually recognize and respect.\n\n---\n\n## The timing question\n\nSocial proof earns its weight when it comes from people who look like your buyer, not just people who like your product. A quote from a VP of Finance at a 200-person SaaS company hits differently than a glowing review from someone your prospect can't map themselves onto.\n\nWhich customer outcome, right now, would make your ideal prospect say \"that's exactly my problem\"? Start there.",
